const CURRICULUM = [
  {
    unit: "Unit I",
    name: "Foundations of Argument",
    lessons: [
      {
        id: "1-1", type: "lesson", title: "What Is Debate?", time: "6 min", level: "Beginner",
        lead: "Debate is the structured clash of ideas — a discipline as old as democracy itself. Understanding what debate is (and isn't) sets the foundation for everything else.",
        body: `
<h2>The Purpose of Debate</h2>
<p>Debate is not about winning arguments at dinner parties. At its core, it is a method for <strong>truth-seeking</strong> through adversarial discourse. Two or more parties present competing positions, challenge each other's reasoning, and allow an audience — or themselves — to arrive at a better understanding of a complex question.</p>
<p>From Athenian democracy to the Oxford Union, from the Lincoln-Douglas debates to the United Nations floor, structured debate has shaped the course of human history. The ability to argue clearly and persuasively is not a gift — it is a learnable skill.</p>
<div class="callout callout-insight">
  <div class="callout-label">💡 Key Insight</div>
  <p>The best debaters are not necessarily the ones who "win." They are the ones who elevate the quality of discourse and force all parties to think more rigorously.</p>
</div>
<h2>Types of Debate</h2>
<p>Debate takes many forms, each with its own rules and conventions:</p>
<table class="compare-table">
  <tr><th>Format</th><th>Description</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Parliamentary</td><td>Government vs. Opposition; motions debated in real time with limited prep</td><td>Speed, adaptability, wit</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Lincoln-Douglas</td><td>One-on-one value debate; emphasis on philosophy and ethics</td><td>Deep logical analysis</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Policy Debate</td><td>Teams research a single resolution all year; evidence-heavy</td><td>Research, evidence, speed</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Moot Court</td><td>Legal argument simulation; strict procedural rules</td><td>Legal reasoning, procedure</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Oxford-Style</td><td>Audience votes before and after; winner judged by vote swing</td><td>Persuasion of undecideds</td></tr>
</table>
<h2>The Anatomy of a Debate Round</h2>
<p>Whatever the format, most debates share a common skeleton:</p>
<div class="framework-grid">
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">1</div><div class="fc-name">Opening</div><div class="fc-desc">Define key terms, establish your position, preview your arguments</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">2</div><div class="fc-name">Substantive</div><div class="fc-desc">Develop your main arguments with evidence and logical reasoning</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">3</div><div class="fc-name">Rebuttal</div><div class="fc-desc">Directly attack your opponent's case and defend your own</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">4</div><div class="fc-name">Summary</div><div class="fc-desc">Crystallize the debate — why did your side win the key clashes?</div></div>
</div>
<h2>Mindset: Steel-Manning, Not Straw-Manning</h2>
<p>The hallmark of a great debater is the ability to <strong>steelman</strong> — to understand and articulate the opposing position at its strongest, before refuting it. The opposite — the <strong>straw man</strong> — is attacking a weakened caricature of your opponent's argument. Great debaters engage with the best version of opposing ideas.</p>
<div class="callout callout-tip">
  <div class="callout-label">🎯 Practice Tip</div>
  <p>Before your next debate, write out the three strongest arguments for the <em>opposing</em> side. If you can't, you're not ready to debate your own position effectively.</p>
</div>`
      },
      {
        id: "1-2", type: "lesson", title: "Ethos, Pathos, Logos", time: "9 min", level: "Beginner",
        lead: "Aristotle's three modes of persuasion — established over 2,000 years ago — remain the most powerful framework for understanding how arguments work.",
        body: `
<h2>The Three Pillars of Persuasion</h2>
<p>In his <em>Rhetoric</em>, Aristotle identified that all persuasion rests on three appeals. Every effective argument uses all three in balance — lean too heavily on one and your case becomes lopsided.</p>
<div class="framework-grid">
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--blue)">E</div><div class="fc-name">Ethos — Credibility</div><div class="fc-desc">Why should the audience trust <em>you</em>? Establish authority, expertise, and good character before you make your case.</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--red)">P</div><div class="fc-name">Pathos — Emotion</div><div class="fc-desc">Connect emotionally with your audience. Stories, vivid imagery, and appeals to shared values all activate pathos.</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--green)">L</div><div class="fc-name">Logos — Logic</div><div class="fc-desc">The logical structure of your argument: evidence, statistics, analogies, and sound reasoning.</div></div>
</div>
<h2>Ethos in Practice</h2>
<p>Ethos is not just about your credentials — it's about how you carry yourself. A calm, confident debater who acknowledges the complexity of an issue projects more ethos than one who claims to have all the answers. Cite reputable sources. Acknowledge strong counterarguments before dismissing them. Show intellectual honesty.</p>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">Example — Weak vs. Strong Ethos</div>
  <p><strong>Weak:</strong> "Trust me, I know a lot about this topic."<br><strong>Strong:</strong> "The WHO's 2023 report, peer-reviewed in The Lancet, found that..."</p>
</div>
<h2>Pathos in Practice</h2>
<p>Pathos is the engine of persuasion — but it must be fueled by truth. A story that illustrates a real problem is pathos at its finest. Manufactured emotional manipulation that distorts the facts is propaganda. The distinction matters enormously in debate.</p>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">Example — Using Pathos Effectively</div>
  <p>"For every statistic we cite, there is a person behind it. Maria, a nurse in a rural hospital, waited 14 months for basic supplies that this policy would have guaranteed within weeks."</p>
</div>
<div class="callout callout-warning">
  <div class="callout-label">⚠️ Warning</div>
  <p>Pathos without logos is manipulation. In competitive debate, judges will penalize emotional appeals that substitute for, rather than supplement, logical argument.</p>
</div>
<h2>Logos in Practice</h2>
<p>Logos is the architecture of your argument. It includes: deductive reasoning (from general principles to specific conclusions), inductive reasoning (from specific cases to general conclusions), and analogical reasoning (comparing to parallel cases). Each has strengths and vulnerabilities that opponents can exploit.</p>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">Example — Logos Under Attack</div>
  <p><strong>Claim:</strong> "Countries with stricter gun laws have lower homicide rates."<br><strong>Logos attack:</strong> "Correlation is not causation — homicide rates are also explained by poverty, urbanization, and policing strategy. The mechanism is not established."</p>
</div>
<h2>The Balance</h2>
<p>Different audiences and contexts demand different mixes. A scientific conference weights logos heavily. A political rally runs on pathos. A courtroom requires ethos from witnesses and logos from lawyers. Skilled debaters read the room and adjust.</p>`
      },
      {
        id: "1-3", type: "lesson", title: "Argument Structure: SEEC & Toulmin", time: "10 min", level: "Beginner",
        lead: "An argument is not just a claim — it's a structured chain of reasoning from evidence to conclusion. Two frameworks help you build and evaluate arguments rigorously.",
        body: `
<h2>Why Structure Matters</h2>
<p>An unstructured argument is like a building without a blueprint — it might stand for a while, but it collapses under pressure. Structured arguments are harder to attack because every component is clear and defensible. Your opponent must engage with each piece, not wave away a vague impression.</p>
<h2>The SEEC Framework</h2>
<p>SEEC is the most practical framework for rapid argument construction in competitive debate. Master it until it becomes automatic.</p>
<div class="framework-grid">
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">S</div><div class="fc-name">Statement</div><div class="fc-desc">Your claim in one clear, falsifiable sentence. Avoid hedging.</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">E</div><div class="fc-name">Explanation</div><div class="fc-desc">The mechanism: <em>why</em> is your claim true? What is the causal chain?</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">E</div><div class="fc-name">Evidence</div><div class="fc-desc">Data, studies, expert opinion, or concrete examples that prove it.</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter">C</div><div class="fc-name">Conclusion</div><div class="fc-desc">Tie it back to the motion. Why does this argument win the debate?</div></div>
</div>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">SEEC in Action</div>
  <p><strong>[S]</strong> Automation will cause structural unemployment in the short to medium term.<br><strong>[E]</strong> As AI replaces routine cognitive and physical tasks, workers in those roles face displacement faster than equivalent new roles can be created in other sectors.<br><strong>[E]</strong> The World Economic Forum projects a net loss of 85 million jobs by 2025, with new job creation lagging displacement by 5–10 years in most economies.<br><strong>[C]</strong> Therefore, a managed transition — not unfettered automation — is what this motion demands.</p>
</div>
<h2>The Toulmin Model</h2>
<p>Philosopher Stephen Toulmin developed a more granular model for analyzing arguments, particularly useful in academic and legal contexts.</p>
<table class="compare-table">
  <tr><th>Component</th><th>Function</th><th>Example</th></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Claim</td><td>Your conclusion or position</td><td>"We should raise the minimum wage"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Data</td><td>Evidence supporting the claim</td><td>"40% of workers earn below living wage"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Warrant</td><td>The logical bridge between data and claim</td><td>"Employers can afford wage increases given current profit margins"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Backing</td><td>Support for the warrant itself</td><td>"Corporate profits hit record highs in 2023 despite inflation"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Qualifier</td><td>Limitations on the claim</td><td>"In most OECD economies, under normal economic conditions"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Rebuttal</td><td>Conditions under which the claim fails</td><td>"Except in highly automated sectors where labor costs are already minimal"</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="callout callout-tip">
  <div class="callout-label">💡 Pro Move</div>
  <p>Attack your opponent's <strong>warrant</strong>, not just their data. Data can be disputed but rarely disproved in a debate. The warrant — the logical connection between evidence and claim — is often far more vulnerable.</p>
</div>
<h2>Deductive vs. Inductive Reasoning</h2>
<p><strong>Deductive</strong> reasoning moves from general premises to specific conclusions. If the premises are true and the logic is valid, the conclusion must be true. This is the gold standard — but the premises must be bulletproof.<br><br><strong>Inductive</strong> reasoning moves from specific observations to general conclusions. It's the basis of all empirical science, but it only establishes probability, not certainty. Your opponent can always find the counter-example.</p>`
