        body: `
<h2>What Makes a Rebuttal Effective?</h2>
<p>Most debaters confuse disagreement with rebuttal. "That's wrong" is not a rebuttal. An effective rebuttal has three qualities: it is <strong>precise</strong> (it attacks a specific component of the argument), <strong>evidenced</strong> (it doesn't just deny, it disproves), and <strong>consequential</strong> (it explains why winning this point matters to the overall debate).</p>
<h2>The PEEL Rebuttal Framework</h2>
<div class="framework-grid">
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--purple)">P</div><div class="fc-name">Point</div><div class="fc-desc">Name your opponent's argument precisely. "My opponent claims that…"</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--red)">E</div><div class="fc-name">Explain</div><div class="fc-desc">Identify the flaw: weak evidence, faulty logic, false premise, or irrelevance.</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--blue)">E</div><div class="fc-name">Evidence</div><div class="fc-desc">Bring in counter-evidence or expose what evidence they failed to consider.</div></div>
  <div class="framework-card"><div class="fc-letter" style="color:var(--green)">L</div><div class="fc-name">Link</div><div class="fc-desc">Explain why this rebuttal matters — what does it mean for the overall debate?</div></div>
</div>
<h2>Advanced Rebuttal Techniques</h2>
<h3>The Concede-and-Pivot</h3>
<p>One of the most disarming techniques: agree with part of your opponent's argument, then show it actually supports <em>your</em> case. This signals intellectual honesty while pulling the rug from under your opponent.</p>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">Concede & Pivot in Action</div>
  <p>"My opponent is absolutely right that this policy is expensive — we've never disputed that. But here is what they haven't told you: every pound spent upfront saves £3.70 in long-term healthcare costs. This is not a drain on the public purse. It <em>is</em> the public purse being used wisely."</p>
</div>
<h3>The Turn</h3>
<p>The most powerful rebuttal move: arguing that your opponent's evidence actually supports <em>your</em> position. When you "turn" an argument, your opponent's work becomes your work. The debate score flips twice — you lose a point when they make the argument, but gain it back when you turn it.</p>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">Turning an Argument</div>
  <p>Opponent: "Economic growth in fossil fuel sectors supports millions of jobs — we can't abandon them."<br>Turn: "My opponent is correct that fossil fuel sectors employ millions — which is exactly why we need a managed green transition <em>now</em>. Every year we delay is another year those workers are not retrained for the inevitable shift. The compassionate position is action, not inaction."</p>
</div>
<h3>Exposing the Link Gap</h3>
<p>Most weak arguments fail at the link — the logical connection between evidence and conclusion. The evidence might be true, but the conclusion doesn't follow. Identify this gap explicitly.</p>
<div class="callout callout-tip">
  <div class="callout-label">🎯 Link-Gap Attack Template</div>
  <p>"My opponent offers [evidence]. But they have not explained how this leads to [their conclusion]. There are at least three alternative explanations: [X], [Y], and [Z]. Their case collapses if even one of these is true."</p>
</div>
<h2>What NOT to Do in Rebuttal</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Don't over-rebut.</strong> Addressing every single point your opponent makes signals you're playing defence. Pick the two or three that matter most.</li>
  <li><strong>Don't ignore the strongest argument.</strong> Judges will notice. If you can't beat your opponent's best point, acknowledge its strength while explaining why it doesn't decide the debate.</li>
  <li><strong>Don't make new arguments in rebuttal.</strong> Most formats prohibit this, and it looks evasive — like you're hiding the argument from scrutiny.</li>
</ul>`
