        lead: "Cross-examination is where debates are won and lost. Done well, it dismantles your opponent's case in two minutes. Done poorly, it hands them the debate.",
        body: `
<h2>What Cross-Examination Is For</h2>
<p>Cross-ex is not a debate — it's an interrogation. Your goal is never to argue with your opponent. Your goal is to extract concessions, expose inconsistencies, and set up arguments you will make in your next speech. The most powerful cross-ex questions are ones to which you already know the answer.</p>
<p>There are four legitimate goals in cross-examination:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Get concessions</strong> that support your own case</li>
  <li><strong>Clarify positions</strong> to expose their weaknesses or contradictions</li>
  <li><strong>Expose the link gap</strong> between their evidence and their conclusions</li>
  <li><strong>Undermine credibility</strong> of their sources or methodology</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Funnel Technique</h2>
<p>The funnel is the most effective cross-ex structure: start with broad questions the opponent must agree with, then progressively narrow until you reach a point that contradicts their case. By the time they see where you're going, it's too late — they've already agreed to the premises.</p>
<div class="callout callout-example">
  <div class="callout-label">The Funnel in Action</div>
  <p><strong>Q:</strong> "You agree that economic growth is generally a good thing?"<br>
<strong>A:</strong> "Yes."<br>
<strong>Q:</strong> "And you accept that the IMF projects this policy will reduce GDP by 2%?"<br>
<strong>A:</strong> "In the short term, yes."<br>
<strong>Q:</strong> "So you're proposing a policy that you agree reduces something you agree is beneficial. Can you explain how that's a net positive?"</p>
</div>
<h2>Question Types</h2>
<table class="compare-table">
  <tr><th>Type</th><th>When to Use</th><th>Example</th></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Closed (Yes/No)</td><td>When forcing a concession</td><td>"Does your evidence come from a peer-reviewed study?"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Clarifying</td><td>When exposing vagueness</td><td>"When you say 'most experts,' how many sources are you referring to?"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Hypothetical</td><td>Testing the limits of a position</td><td>"If unemployment doubled as a result, would you still support this?"</td></tr>
  <tr><td class="highlight">Source challenge</td><td>Undermining evidence</td><td>"Your study was funded by the industry it was evaluating — does that concern you?"</td></tr>
</table>
<h2>The Cardinal Rules of Cross-Ex</h2>
<div class="fallacy-grid">
  <div class="fallacy-card red"><div class="fallacy-name">Never ask open questions</div><div class="fallacy-def">Open questions give your opponent a podium. You lose control immediately. Every question should have a narrow, answerable scope.</div></div>
  <div class="fallacy-card amber"><div class="fallacy-name">Never argue</div><div class="fallacy-def">If your opponent says something outrageous, make a note and destroy it in your speech. Don't debate during cross-ex — you'll look flustered.</div></div>
  <div class="fallacy-card purple"><div class="fallacy-name">Never telegraph your destination</div><div class="fallacy-def">As soon as your opponent knows where the funnel leads, they'll evade. Use indirect paths to your target question.</div></div>
  <div class="fallacy-card blue"><div class="fallacy-name">Cut off evasion — politely</div><div class="fallacy-def">"With respect, that doesn't answer my question. [Repeat the question.]" Do this twice. If they still evade, move on — judges notice evasion.</div></div>
</div>
<h2>Answering Cross-Examination (Defence)</h2>
<p>When you're on the receiving end, the rules invert. You want to: give minimal answers (don't volunteer information), challenge the framing of leading questions, and never let the questioner put words in your mouth. If a question contains a false premise, attack the premise: "I reject the framing of that question — it assumes X, which we have demonstrated is false."</p>`
